{"findings":[{"id":"F-001","severity":"Critical","confidence":"high","title":"Proxy selector `0x03b79c24` can transfer custodied `weETH` to an attacker-controlled recipient","locations":["unverified_54cd.sol:43","unverified_54cd.sol:58","unverified_54cd.sol:65"],"claim":"The forked PoC shows that a direct call to the live ERC1967 proxy with selector `0x03b79c24` and an attacker-chosen recipient succeeds, after which the attacker contract has enough `weETH` to pay the Uniswap V3 swap callback and unwrap `114.534059890882021484` WETH to ETH. This is strong evidence that the proxied implementation exposed an externally callable path that released the proxy's `weETH` to an arbitrary receiver without effective access control.","impact":"Any attacker can drain protocol-held `weETH` from the proxy and convert it into liquid assets, causing direct theft of TVL.","paths":["Call the proxy directly with selector `0x03b79c24` and an attacker-controlled recipient","Receive transferable `weETH` on the attacker contract","Swap the stolen position through the Uniswap V3 pool and pay the callback with the drained `weETH`","Unwrap the acquired WETH and forward the ETH profit to the attacker"],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex"]}],"rejected_candidates":[{"title":"Asset release path appears unbounded by per-user accounting","source_agents":["codex"],"reason":"The local source only proves that the selector released valuable `weETH`; it does not expose the underlying accounting logic, so there is not enough evidence to conclude that per-user share/debt limits were specifically bypassed."},{"title":"Sensitive maintenance or recovery selector appears left reachable on the asset-holding proxy","source_agents":["codex"],"reason":"The raw selector call is suspicious, but without the proxied implementation or ABI there is not enough evidence to classify it as a forgotten maintenance/recovery routine rather than some other vulnerable external function."}]}
